00:00:00.110 --> 00:00:24.870
PROFESSOR: And this is a
question based on where we

00:00:24.870 --> 00:00:27.730
left off on Wednesday -- we were
talking about Coulomb's

00:00:27.730 --> 00:00:31.750
force law to describe the
interaction between two

00:00:31.750 --> 00:00:35.330
particles, and good job, most
of you got this correct.

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:39.910
So, what we're looking at here
is the force when we have two

00:00:39.910 --> 00:00:42.220
charged particles, one positive,
one negative --

00:00:42.220 --> 00:00:46.230
here, the nucleus
and an electron.

00:00:46.230 --> 00:00:49.810
So, I know this is a simple
example and I can see everyone

00:00:49.810 --> 00:00:52.210
pretty much got it right, and
probably those that didn't

00:00:52.210 --> 00:00:55.390
actually made some sort of
clicker error is my guess.

00:00:55.390 --> 00:00:59.410
But I wanted to use this to
point out that in this class

00:00:59.410 --> 00:01:03.150
in general, any time you see
an equation to explain a

00:01:03.150 --> 00:01:06.320
certain phenomenon, such as here
looking at force, it's a

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:09.310
good idea to check yourself by
first plugging it into the

00:01:09.310 --> 00:01:12.220
actual equation, so you can
plug in infinity and this

00:01:12.220 --> 00:01:15.050
equation here, and what you
would see is, of course, the

00:01:15.050 --> 00:01:18.460
force, if you just solve the
math problem goes to zero.

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:21.240
But you can also look at it
qualitatively, so, if you

00:01:21.240 --> 00:01:25.060
think about the force between
the electron and the proton,

00:01:25.060 --> 00:01:27.720
you could just qualitatively
think about what's happening.

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:29.940
If they're close together
there's a certain force --

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:32.983
they're attracted because they
have opposite charges, but as

00:01:32.983 --> 00:01:35.470
that gets further and further
away, that force is going to

00:01:35.470 --> 00:01:38.695
get smaller and smaller, and
eventually the force is going

00:01:38.695 --> 00:01:39.860
to approach zero.

00:01:39.860 --> 00:01:42.690
So, it's a good kind of mental
check as we go through this

00:01:42.690 --> 00:01:45.130
course to remember every time
there's an equation, usually

00:01:45.130 --> 00:01:47.820
there's a very good reason for
that equation, and you can go

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:50.600
ahead and just use your
qualitative knowledge, you

00:01:50.600 --> 00:01:52.870
don't have to just always stick
with the math to check

00:01:52.870 --> 00:01:54.640
and justify your answers.

00:01:54.640 --> 00:01:58.740
So, we can get started with
today's lecture notes.

00:01:58.740 --> 00:02:02.880
And, as I mentioned, we left
off and as we started back

00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:06.930
here to describe the atom and
how the atom holds together

00:02:06.930 --> 00:02:11.010
the nucleus and the electron
using classical mechanics.

00:02:11.010 --> 00:02:13.820
And today we'll finish that
discussion, and, of course,

00:02:13.820 --> 00:02:17.830
point out actually the failure
of classical mechanics to

00:02:17.830 --> 00:02:21.960
appropriately describe what's
going on in an atom.

00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:24.640
So, then we'll get to turn to
a new kind of mechanics or

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:28.310
quantum mechanics, which will
in fact be able to describe

00:02:28.310 --> 00:02:31.920
what's happening on this very,
very small size scale -- so on

00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:33.980
the atomic size scale on the
order of nanometers or

00:02:33.980 --> 00:02:37.060
angstroms, very small
particles.

00:02:37.060 --> 00:02:39.430
And the reason that quantum
mechanics is going to work

00:02:39.430 --> 00:02:42.020
where classical mechanics
fails is that classical

00:02:42.020 --> 00:02:45.980
mechanics did not take into
account the fact that matter

00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:49.720
has both wave-like and
particle-like properties, and

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:52.700
light has both wave-like and
particle-like properties.

00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:55.280
So, we'll take a little bit of a
step back after we introduce

00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:58.880
quantum mechanics, and talk
about light as a wave, and the

00:02:58.880 --> 00:03:02.880
characteristic of waves, and
then light as a particle.

00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:08.070
And one example of this is in
the photoelectric effect.

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:12.000
So, we just talked about the
force law to describe the

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:15.090
interaction between a proton
and an electron.

00:03:15.090 --> 00:03:18.150
You told me that when the
distance went to infinity, the

00:03:18.150 --> 00:03:19.610
force went to zero.

00:03:19.610 --> 00:03:23.300
What happens instead when the
distance goes to zero?

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:26.810
What happens to the force?

00:03:26.810 --> 00:03:27.080
Yeah.

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:30.010
So, the force actually goes to
infinity, and specifically it

00:03:30.010 --> 00:03:31.910
goes to negative infinity.

00:03:31.910 --> 00:03:34.290
Infinity is the force when we're
thinking about it and

00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:37.270
our brains, negative infinity
is when we actually plug it

00:03:37.270 --> 00:03:39.870
into the equation here, and the
reason is the convention

00:03:39.870 --> 00:03:42.280
that the negative sign is just
telling us the direction that

00:03:42.280 --> 00:03:46.000
the force is coming together
instead of pushing apart.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:49.100
So, we can use Coulomb's force
law to think about the force

00:03:49.100 --> 00:03:52.130
between these two particles --
and it does that, it tells us

00:03:52.130 --> 00:03:54.720
the force is a function
of that distance.

00:03:54.720 --> 00:03:57.380
But what it does not tell us,
which if we're trying to

00:03:57.380 --> 00:04:02.460
describe an atom we really want
to know, is what happens

00:04:02.460 --> 00:04:04.750
to the distance as
time passes?

00:04:04.750 --> 00:04:07.570
So, r is a function of time.

00:04:07.570 --> 00:04:10.770
But luckily for us, there's a
classical equation of motion

00:04:10.770 --> 00:04:14.190
that will, in fact, describe how
the electron and nucleus

00:04:14.190 --> 00:04:17.350
change position or change
their radius as

00:04:17.350 --> 00:04:19.280
a function of time.

00:04:19.280 --> 00:04:22.390
So, that's -- does anyone know
which classical law of motion

00:04:22.390 --> 00:04:25.370
that would be?

00:04:25.370 --> 00:04:28.680
Yup, so it's going to be
Newton's second law, force

00:04:28.680 --> 00:04:31.070
equals mass times acceleration
-- those of you that are quick

00:04:31.070 --> 00:04:35.130
page-turners, have a little
one-up on answering that.

00:04:35.130 --> 00:04:39.070
And that tells us force as a
function of acceleration, we

00:04:39.070 --> 00:04:42.070
want to know it though as a
function of radius, so we can

00:04:42.070 --> 00:04:45.520
just take the first derivative
and get ourselves to velocity.

00:04:45.520 --> 00:04:49.570
So, force is equal to
mass times dv /dt.

00:04:49.570 --> 00:04:52.120
But, of course, we want to go
all the way to distance, so we

00:04:52.120 --> 00:04:55.130
take the second derivative and
we have this equation for

00:04:55.130 --> 00:04:56.670
force here.

00:04:56.670 --> 00:04:59.640
And what we can do in order
to bring the two equations

00:04:59.640 --> 00:05:04.940
together, is to plug in the
Coulomb force law right here.

00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:08.170
So, now we have our Coulomb
force law all plugged in here,

00:05:08.170 --> 00:05:10.930
and we have this differential
equation that we could solve,

00:05:10.930 --> 00:05:14.020
if we wanted to figure out
what the force was at

00:05:14.020 --> 00:05:17.470
different times t, or at
different positions of r.

00:05:17.470 --> 00:05:19.810
So, all you will have the
opportunity to solve

00:05:19.810 --> 00:05:21.920
differential equations in
your math courses here.

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:24.310
We won't do it in this
chemistry course.

00:05:24.310 --> 00:05:26.260
In later chemistry courses,
you'll also get to solve

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:27.800
differential equations.

00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:30.730
But instead in this chemistry
course, I will just tell you

00:05:30.730 --> 00:05:33.030
the solutions to differential
equations.

00:05:33.030 --> 00:05:36.260
And what we can do is we can
start with some initial value

00:05:36.260 --> 00:05:40.230
of r, and here I write r being
ten angstroms. That's a good

00:05:40.230 --> 00:05:42.220
approximation when we're talking
about atoms, because

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:43.630
that's about the size
of and atom.

00:05:43.630 --> 00:05:46.900
So, let's say we start off
at the distance being ten

00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:49.840
angstroms. We can plug that
into this differential

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:53.940
equation that we'll have and
solve it, and what we find out

00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:57.540
is that r actually goes to zero
at a time that's equal to

00:05:57.540 --> 00:06:00.790
10 to the negative 10 seconds.

00:06:00.790 --> 00:06:04.130
So, let's think qualitatively
for a second about what that

00:06:04.130 --> 00:06:06.060
means or what the real
meaning of that is.

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:09.440
What that is telling us is that
according to Newtonian

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:13.630
mechanics and Coulomb's force
law, is that the electron

00:06:13.630 --> 00:06:16.460
should actually plummet into
the nucleus in 0.1

00:06:16.460 --> 00:06:16.730
nanoseconds.

00:06:16.730 --> 00:06:22.590
So, we have a little bit
of a problem here.

00:06:22.590 --> 00:06:26.460
And the problem that we have
is that what we're figuring

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:30.310
out mathematically is not
exactly matching up with what

00:06:30.310 --> 00:06:33.060
we're observing experimentally.

00:06:33.060 --> 00:06:36.330
And, in fact, it's often kind of
difficult to experimentally

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:39.540
test your mathematical
predictions -- a lot of people

00:06:39.540 --> 00:06:42.220
spend many, many years testing
one single mathematical

00:06:42.220 --> 00:06:43.260
prediction.

00:06:43.260 --> 00:06:46.670
But, I think all of us right
now can probably test this

00:06:46.670 --> 00:06:49.850
prediction right here, and we're
observing that, in fact,

00:06:49.850 --> 00:06:52.960
all of us and all the atoms we
can see are not immediately

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:56.140
collapsing in less than
a nanosecond.

00:06:56.140 --> 00:06:59.320
So, just, if you can take what
I'm saying for a moment right

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:03.140
now that in fact this should
collapse in this very small

00:07:03.140 --> 00:07:06.290
time frame, we have to see that
there's a problem with

00:07:06.290 --> 00:07:09.860
one of these two things, either
the Coulomb force law

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:12.680
or Newtonian mechanics.

00:07:12.680 --> 00:07:18.730
So, what do you guys think is
probably the issue here?

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:23.070
So, it's Newtonian mechanics,
and the reason for this is

00:07:23.070 --> 00:07:26.510
because Newtonian mechanics does
not work on this very,

00:07:26.510 --> 00:07:27.990
very small size scale.

00:07:27.990 --> 00:07:31.220
As we said, Newtonian mechanics
does work in most

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:34.580
cases, it does work when we're
discussing things that we can

00:07:34.580 --> 00:07:36.920
see, it does work even
on things that are

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:38.090
too small to measure.

00:07:38.090 --> 00:07:41.570
But once we got to the atomic
size scale, what happens is we

00:07:41.570 --> 00:07:45.880
need to be taking into account
the fact that matter has these

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:48.760
wave-like properties, and we'll
learn more about that

00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:51.150
later, but essentially classical
mechanics does not

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:52.930
take that into account at all.

00:07:52.930 --> 00:07:55.330
So, we need a new kind of
mechanics, which is quantum

00:07:55.330 --> 00:07:57.580
mechanics, which will accurately
explain the

00:07:57.580 --> 00:08:01.590
behavior of molecules
on this small scale.

00:08:01.590 --> 00:08:05.530
So, as I mentioned, the real
key to quantum mechanics is

00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:08.190
that it's treating matter not
just like it's a particle,

00:08:08.190 --> 00:08:10.680
which is what we were just
doing, but also like it's a

00:08:10.680 --> 00:08:13.350
wave, and it treats light
that way, too.

00:08:13.350 --> 00:08:16.340
The second important point to
quantum mechanics is that it

00:08:16.340 --> 00:08:20.280
actually considers the fact that
light consists of these

00:08:20.280 --> 00:08:23.590
discrete packets or
particle-like pieces of

00:08:23.590 --> 00:08:25.570
energy, which are
called photons.

00:08:25.570 --> 00:08:28.300
And if you think about what's
actually happening here, this

00:08:28.300 --> 00:08:30.840
second point that light
consists of photons is

00:08:30.840 --> 00:08:33.840
actually the same thing as
saying that light shows

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:37.190
particle-like properties, but
that's such an important point

00:08:37.190 --> 00:08:41.150
that I put it separately, and
we'll cover that separately as

00:08:41.150 --> 00:08:43.780
we go along.

00:08:43.780 --> 00:08:48.500
So, we now have this new way
of thinking about how a

00:08:48.500 --> 00:08:51.520
nucleus and an electron can
hang together, and this is

00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:54.480
quantum mechanics, and we can
use this to come up with a new

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:58.140
way to describe our atom and the
behavior of atoms. But the

00:08:58.140 --> 00:09:01.080
problem is before we do this,
it makes sense to take a

00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:03.385
little bit of a step back and
actually make sure we're all

00:09:03.385 --> 00:09:05.690
on the same page and
understanding why quantum

00:09:05.690 --> 00:09:09.110
mechanics is so important and
how it works, and specifically

00:09:09.110 --> 00:09:12.210
understanding what we mean when
we say that light is both

00:09:12.210 --> 00:09:14.770
a particle and a wave, and that
matter is both a particle

00:09:14.770 --> 00:09:18.640
and a wave. So, we'll move on to
this discussion of light as

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:22.080
a wave, and we really won't
pick up into going back to

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:26.370
applying quantum mechanics to
the atom until Friday, but in

00:09:26.370 --> 00:09:28.970
the meantime, we'll really get
to understand the wave

00:09:28.970 --> 00:09:33.220
particle duality of light
and of matter.

00:09:33.220 --> 00:09:36.640
So, we'll start with thinking
about some properties of waves

00:09:36.640 --> 00:09:38.430
that are going to be applicable
to all waves that

00:09:38.430 --> 00:09:40.750
we're talking about, including
light waves.

00:09:40.750 --> 00:09:44.810
The easiest kind of waves for us
to picture are ocean waves

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:47.810
or water waves, because we can,
in fact, see them, but

00:09:47.810 --> 00:09:50.110
they have similar properties
to all waves.

00:09:50.110 --> 00:09:53.820
And those properties include
that you have this periodic

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:55.940
variation of some property.

00:09:55.940 --> 00:09:58.320
So, when we're talking about
water waves, the property

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:01.650
we're discussing is just
the water level.

00:10:01.650 --> 00:10:04.780
So, for example, we have this
average level, and then it can

00:10:04.780 --> 00:10:08.160
go high where we have the peak,
or it can go very low.

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:10.990
We can also discuss sound waves,
so again it's just the

00:10:10.990 --> 00:10:14.060
periodic variation of some
property -- in this case we're

00:10:14.060 --> 00:10:17.700
talking about density, so we
have high density areas and

00:10:17.700 --> 00:10:20.730
low density areas.

00:10:20.730 --> 00:10:23.880
So, regardless of the type of
wave that we're talking about,

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:26.390
there's some common definitions
that we want to

00:10:26.390 --> 00:10:28.070
make sure that we're all
able to use, and

00:10:28.070 --> 00:10:28.920
the first is amplitude.

00:10:28.920 --> 00:10:32.060
And when we're talking about
the amplitude of the wave,

00:10:32.060 --> 00:10:33.820
we're talking about
the deviation from

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:35.290
that average level.

00:10:35.290 --> 00:10:38.440
So, if we define the average
level as zero, you can have

00:10:38.440 --> 00:10:41.760
either a positive amplitude
or a negative amplitude.

00:10:41.760 --> 00:10:43.930
So, sometimes people get
confused when they're solving

00:10:43.930 --> 00:10:46.430
problems and call the amplitude
this distance all

00:10:46.430 --> 00:10:49.760
the way from the max to the
min, but it's only half of

00:10:49.760 --> 00:10:53.470
that because we're only going
back to the average level.

00:10:53.470 --> 00:10:55.940
So, what we really want to
talk about here is light

00:10:55.940 --> 00:10:59.360
waves, and light waves have the
same properties as these

00:10:59.360 --> 00:11:02.550
other kind of waves in that
they're the periodic variation

00:11:02.550 --> 00:11:04.080
of some property.

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:06.280
So, when we're discussing
light waves, what we're

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:10.130
talking about is actually
light or electromagnetic

00:11:10.130 --> 00:11:12.160
radiation, is what we'll
be calling it

00:11:12.160 --> 00:11:13.400
throughout the course.

00:11:13.400 --> 00:11:15.310
And that's the periodic
variation

00:11:15.310 --> 00:11:17.040
of an electric field.

00:11:17.040 --> 00:11:20.540
So, instead of having the
periodic variation of water,

00:11:20.540 --> 00:11:24.040
or the periodic variation of
air density, here we're

00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:25.810
talking about an
electric field.

00:11:25.810 --> 00:11:28.940
We know what an electric field
is, it's just a space through

00:11:28.940 --> 00:11:30.860
which a Coulomb force
operates.

00:11:30.860 --> 00:11:32.660
And the important thing to
think about when you're

00:11:32.660 --> 00:11:35.620
talking about the fact that it's
a periodic variation, is

00:11:35.620 --> 00:11:38.800
if you put a charged particle
somewhere into an electric

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:42.270
field, it will, of course, go in
a certain direction toward

00:11:42.270 --> 00:11:43.990
the charge it's attracted to.

00:11:43.990 --> 00:11:46.380
But you need to think about the
difference, if you have a

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:49.560
particle here on your wave, it
will go in one direction.

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:52.990
But remember, waves don't just
have magnitude, they also do

00:11:52.990 --> 00:11:55.150
have direction.

00:11:55.150 --> 00:11:58.250
So, if instead you put your
particle somewhere down here

00:11:58.250 --> 00:12:01.520
on the electric field, or on the
wave, the electric field

00:12:01.520 --> 00:12:04.410
will now be in the other
direction, so your particle

00:12:04.410 --> 00:12:06.960
will be pushed the other way.

00:12:06.960 --> 00:12:09.460
And from physics you know that,
of course, if we have a

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:12.590
propagating electric field, we
also have a perpendicular

00:12:12.590 --> 00:12:14.970
magnetic field that's going
back and forth.

00:12:14.970 --> 00:12:18.730
But in terms of worrying about
using the concepts of a wave

00:12:18.730 --> 00:12:21.810
to solve chemistry problems in
this course, we can actually

00:12:21.810 --> 00:12:26.030
put aside the fact, and only
focus on the electric field

00:12:26.030 --> 00:12:28.210
part of things, because that's
what's going to be interacting

00:12:28.210 --> 00:12:32.780
with our charged particles,
such as our electrons.

00:12:32.780 --> 00:12:36.610
So, other properties of waves
that you probably are all

00:12:36.610 --> 00:12:39.360
familiar with but I just want
to review is the idea of a

00:12:39.360 --> 00:12:40.970
wavelength.

00:12:40.970 --> 00:12:43.430
If we're talking about the
wavelength of a wave, we're

00:12:43.430 --> 00:12:45.930
just talking about the distance
that there is between

00:12:45.930 --> 00:12:50.260
successive maxima, or of course,
we can also be talking

00:12:50.260 --> 00:12:52.780
about the distance between
successive minima.

00:12:52.780 --> 00:12:55.420
Basically, we can take any point
on the wave, and it's

00:12:55.420 --> 00:12:59.090
the distance to that same point
later on in the wave.

00:12:59.090 --> 00:13:01.580
So, that's what we call
one wavelength.

00:13:01.580 --> 00:13:05.300
We also commonly discuss the
frequency of a wave, and the

00:13:05.300 --> 00:13:08.270
frequency is just the number of
cycles that that wave goes

00:13:08.270 --> 00:13:10.310
through per unit time.

00:13:10.310 --> 00:13:13.700
So, by a cycle we'd basically
mean how many times we cycle

00:13:13.700 --> 00:13:15.910
through a complete wavelength.

00:13:15.910 --> 00:13:19.240
So, if something cycles through
five wavelengths in a

00:13:19.240 --> 00:13:21.780
single second, we would just say
that the frequency of that

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:27.170
wave is five per second.

00:13:27.170 --> 00:13:30.110
We can also mathematically
describe what's going on here

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:32.260
other than just graphing it.

00:13:32.260 --> 00:13:35.760
So, if we want to look at the
mathematical equation of a

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:38.450
wave, we want to describe --
again as I mention, what we're

00:13:38.450 --> 00:13:40.780
describing is the electric
field, we're not worrying

00:13:40.780 --> 00:13:46.050
about the magnetic field here,
as a function of x and t

00:13:46.050 --> 00:13:53.540
that's equal to a cosine [
2 pi x over wavelength,

00:13:53.540 --> 00:13:57.930
minus 2 pi nu t ].

00:13:57.930 --> 00:13:59.260
And note this is the
Greek letter nu.

00:13:59.260 --> 00:14:07.410
This is not a v. Where we have
E, which is equal to the

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:13.300
electric field, what is x?

00:14:13.300 --> 00:14:16.090
STUDENT: Position.

00:14:16.090 --> 00:14:21.610
PROFESSOR: Yup, the position of
the wave. And what about t?

00:14:21.610 --> 00:14:26.600
Yeah, so we're talking about
both position and time.

00:14:26.600 --> 00:14:29.383
So what we can do if we're
talking about a wave is think

00:14:29.383 --> 00:14:31.920
of it both in terms of position
time, but if we're

00:14:31.920 --> 00:14:34.810
trying to visualize this -- for
example if we're actually

00:14:34.810 --> 00:14:37.760
to graph this out, the easiest
thing to do is keep one of

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:46.270
these two variables constant,
either the x or the t, and

00:14:46.270 --> 00:14:49.510
then just consider the
other variable.

00:14:49.510 --> 00:14:52.290
So, for example, if we're to
hold the time constant, this

00:14:52.290 --> 00:14:55.270
makes it a lot simpler of an
equation, because what we can

00:14:55.270 --> 00:14:58.070
end up doing is actually
crossing out

00:14:58.070 --> 00:14:59.810
this whole term here.

00:14:59.810 --> 00:15:03.370
So what we're left with is just
that the electric field

00:15:03.370 --> 00:15:09.630
as a function of distance is a
times cosine of the argument

00:15:09.630 --> 00:15:13.640
there, which is now just
2 pi x over wavelength.

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:15.760
So, what we want to be able to
do, either when we're looking

00:15:15.760 --> 00:15:19.870
at the graph or looking at the
equation up there, is to think

00:15:19.870 --> 00:15:22.020
about different properties of
the wave. For example, to

00:15:22.020 --> 00:15:26.340
think about at what point do we
have the wave where it's at

00:15:26.340 --> 00:15:29.740
its maximum amplitude?

00:15:29.740 --> 00:15:32.700
So, if we think about that, we
need to have a point where

00:15:32.700 --> 00:15:36.020
we're making this argument of
the cosine such that the

00:15:36.020 --> 00:15:39.120
cosine is going to all be equal
to one, so all we're

00:15:39.120 --> 00:15:40.470
left with is that a term.

00:15:40.470 --> 00:15:45.340
So, we can do that basically
any time that we have an

00:15:45.340 --> 00:15:49.430
integer variable that is either
zero or an integer

00:15:49.430 --> 00:15:51.320
variable of the wavelength.

00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:53.800
So, for example, negative
wavelength or positive

00:15:53.800 --> 00:15:56.650
wavelength are two times the
wavelength, because that lets

00:15:56.650 --> 00:15:59.650
us cross out the term with the
wavelength here, and we're

00:15:59.650 --> 00:16:04.760
left with some integer
multiple of just pi.

00:16:04.760 --> 00:16:06.860
So, that's sort of the
mathematically how we get to

00:16:06.860 --> 00:16:09.900
a, but we can also just look
at the graph here, because

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:12.320
every time we go one wavelength,
we can see that

00:16:12.320 --> 00:16:14.940
we're back in a maximum.

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:18.420
So, I mentioned we should be
able to figure out where the

00:16:18.420 --> 00:16:19.740
maximum amplitude is.

00:16:19.740 --> 00:16:22.990
You should also just looking at
an equation, immediately be

00:16:22.990 --> 00:16:26.980
able to figure out what that
maximum amplitude is in terms

00:16:26.980 --> 00:16:30.470
of the height of it just by
looking at that a-term, here

00:16:30.470 --> 00:16:33.200
we should also be able to know
the intensity of any light

00:16:33.200 --> 00:16:36.780
wave, because intensity is just
the amplitude squared.

00:16:36.780 --> 00:16:39.620
So, we should immediately be
able to know how bright or how

00:16:39.620 --> 00:16:42.220
intense a light is just looking
at the wave equation,

00:16:42.220 --> 00:16:47.160
or just by looking at a graph.

00:16:47.160 --> 00:16:49.750
We can also do a similar
thing, and I'll keep my

00:16:49.750 --> 00:16:54.900
distance from the board, but
we can instead be holding x

00:16:54.900 --> 00:16:58.420
constant, for example, putting
x to be equal to zero, and

00:16:58.420 --> 00:17:01.990
then all we're doing is
considering the electric field

00:17:01.990 --> 00:17:03.190
as a function of t.

00:17:03.190 --> 00:17:05.560
So, in this case we're crossing
out the first term

00:17:05.560 --> 00:17:09.430
there, and we're left with
amplitude times the cosine of

00:17:09.430 --> 00:17:13.120
2 pi nu times t.

00:17:13.120 --> 00:17:15.350
And, of course, we can do the
same thing again, we can think

00:17:15.350 --> 00:17:18.710
about when the amplitude is
going to be at its maximum,

00:17:18.710 --> 00:17:22.220
and it's going to be any time
cosine of this term now is

00:17:22.220 --> 00:17:23.490
equal to one.

00:17:23.490 --> 00:17:26.340
So that will be at, for example,
negative 1 over nu,

00:17:26.340 --> 00:17:28.590
or 0, or 1 over nu.

00:17:28.590 --> 00:17:31.090
And again, we can just look at
our graph to figure that out,

00:17:31.090 --> 00:17:35.350
that's exactly where
we're at a maximum.

00:17:35.350 --> 00:17:39.450
So, 1 over nu is another term
we use and we call it the

00:17:39.450 --> 00:17:42.750
period of a wave, and the period
is just the inverse of

00:17:42.750 --> 00:17:44.200
the frequency.

00:17:44.200 --> 00:17:46.450
And if we think about frequency,
that's number of

00:17:46.450 --> 00:17:48.130
cycles per unit time.

00:17:48.130 --> 00:17:51.450
So, for example, number of
cycles per second, whereas the

00:17:51.450 --> 00:17:58.660
period is how much time it takes
for one cycle to occur.

00:17:58.660 --> 00:18:01.680
And when we talk about units of
frequency, in almost every

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:05.000
case, you'll be talking about
number of cycles per second.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:06.900
So, you can just write
inverse second, the

00:18:06.900 --> 00:18:07.700
cycle part is assumed.

00:18:07.700 --> 00:18:13.560
But you'll also frequently see
it called Hertz, so, Hz here.

00:18:13.560 --> 00:18:15.970
So, if you're talking about five
cycles per second, you

00:18:15.970 --> 00:18:18.740
can write five per second, or
you can write five Hertz.

00:18:18.740 --> 00:18:21.360
The one thing you want to keep
in mind though is that Hertz

00:18:21.360 --> 00:18:23.250
does not actually mean
inverse seconds, it

00:18:23.250 --> 00:18:24.900
means cycles per second.

00:18:24.900 --> 00:18:27.760
So, if you're talking about a
car going so many meters per

00:18:27.760 --> 00:18:31.270
second, you can't say it's going
meter Hertz, you have to

00:18:31.270 --> 00:18:31.790
say meters per second.

00:18:31.790 --> 00:18:33.590
So, this really just means
for frequency,

00:18:33.590 --> 00:18:37.090
it's a frequency label.

00:18:37.090 --> 00:18:38.310
Alright.

00:18:38.310 --> 00:18:40.920
So, since we have these terms
defined, we know the frequency

00:18:40.920 --> 00:18:43.440
and the wavelength, it turns
out we can also think about

00:18:43.440 --> 00:18:47.520
the speed of the wave, and
specifically of a light wave,

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:50.790
and speed and is just equal to
the distance that's traveled

00:18:50.790 --> 00:18:53.370
divided by the time
the elapsed.

00:18:53.370 --> 00:18:56.340
And because we've defined these
terms, we have ways to

00:18:56.340 --> 00:18:57.790
describe these things.

00:18:57.790 --> 00:19:00.480
So, we can describe the distance
that's traveled, it's

00:19:00.480 --> 00:19:03.070
just a wavelength here.

00:19:03.070 --> 00:19:06.320
And we can think about how
long it takes for a wave,

00:19:06.320 --> 00:19:09.130
because waves are, we know not
just changing in position, but

00:19:09.130 --> 00:19:11.700
the whole wave is moving forward
with time, we can

00:19:11.700 --> 00:19:15.610
think about how long it takes
for wave to go one wavelength.

00:19:15.610 --> 00:19:18.510
So, one distance that's
equal to lambda.

00:19:18.510 --> 00:19:25.080
So, how much time would that
take, does anyone know?

00:19:25.080 --> 00:19:29.170
So, would it take, for example,
the same amount of

00:19:29.170 --> 00:19:33.680
time as the frequency?

00:19:33.680 --> 00:19:34.910
The period, that's right.

00:19:34.910 --> 00:19:38.470
So, it's going to take one
period to move that long.

00:19:38.470 --> 00:19:42.280
And another way we can say
period is just 1 over nu or 1

00:19:42.280 --> 00:19:45.860
over the frequency So, now
we know both the distance

00:19:45.860 --> 00:19:48.140
traveled and the time
the elapsed.

00:19:48.140 --> 00:19:49.590
So, we can just plug it in.

00:19:49.590 --> 00:19:53.240
Speed is equal to the distance
traveled, which is lambda over

00:19:53.240 --> 00:19:56.950
the time elapsed, which is 1
over nu. so, we can re-write

00:19:56.950 --> 00:20:02.090
that as speed is equal to lambda
times nu, and it turns

00:20:02.090 --> 00:20:04.860
out typically this is reported
in meters per second or

00:20:04.860 --> 00:20:06.810
nanometers per second.

00:20:06.810 --> 00:20:09.750
So, now we have an equation
where we know the relationship

00:20:09.750 --> 00:20:14.350
between speed and wavelength
and frequency, and it turns

00:20:14.350 --> 00:20:17.180
out that we could take any wave,
and as long as we know

00:20:17.180 --> 00:20:19.160
the frequency and the
wavelength, we'll be able to

00:20:19.160 --> 00:20:20.480
figure out the speed.

00:20:20.480 --> 00:20:22.880
But, of course, there's
something very special about

00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:25.190
electromagnetic waves,
electromagnetic

00:20:25.190 --> 00:20:28.020
radiation and the speed.

00:20:28.020 --> 00:20:30.660
And it's not really surprising
for me to tell you that

00:20:30.660 --> 00:20:34.240
electromagnetic radiation has
a constant speed, and that

00:20:34.240 --> 00:20:37.760
speed is what we call the speed
of light, and typically

00:20:37.760 --> 00:20:41.880
we abbreviate that as c, and
that's from the Latin term

00:20:41.880 --> 00:20:45.100
celeritas, which means
speed in Latin.

00:20:45.100 --> 00:20:47.970
That's one of four or five Latin
words I remember from

00:20:47.970 --> 00:20:50.780
four years of high school Latin,
but it comes in handy

00:20:50.780 --> 00:20:53.080
to remember speed of light.

00:20:53.080 --> 00:20:56.760
And some of you may have
memorized what the speed of

00:20:56.760 --> 00:21:00.250
light is in high school -- it's
about 3 times 10 to the 8

00:21:00.250 --> 00:21:01.750
meters per second.

00:21:01.750 --> 00:21:03.990
This is another example of
a constant that you will

00:21:03.990 --> 00:21:06.770
accidentally memorize in this
course as you use it over and

00:21:06.770 --> 00:21:07.310
over again.

00:21:07.310 --> 00:21:10.730
But again, that we will supply
for you on the exam just in

00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:13.160
case you forget it
at that moment.

00:21:13.160 --> 00:21:16.840
And this is a very fast speed,
of course, it's about 700

00:21:16.840 --> 00:21:20.570
million miles per hour.

00:21:20.570 --> 00:21:22.980
So, one way to put that in
perspective is to think about

00:21:22.980 --> 00:21:27.780
how long it takes for a
light beam to get from

00:21:27.780 --> 00:21:28.640
earth to the moon.

00:21:28.640 --> 00:21:32.270
Does anyone have any guesses?

00:21:32.270 --> 00:21:33.980
Eight seconds, that
sounds good.

00:21:33.980 --> 00:21:37.170
Anyone else?

00:21:37.170 --> 00:21:39.810
These are all really good
guesses, so it actually takes

00:21:39.810 --> 00:21:42.500
1.2 seconds for light
to travel from the

00:21:42.500 --> 00:21:43.360
earth to the moon.

00:21:43.360 --> 00:21:46.750
So, we're talking pretty
fast, so that's nice to

00:21:46.750 --> 00:21:48.930
appreciate in itself.

00:21:48.930 --> 00:21:53.560
But other than that point, we
can also think about the fact

00:21:53.560 --> 00:22:00.520
that frequency and wavelength
are related in a way that now

00:22:00.520 --> 00:22:03.260
since we know the speed of
light, if we know one we can

00:22:03.260 --> 00:22:03.950
tell the other.

00:22:03.950 --> 00:22:06.090
So, you can go ahead and switch
us to our clicker

00:22:06.090 --> 00:22:08.720
question here.

00:22:08.720 --> 00:22:13.110
So, we should be able to look
at different types of waves

00:22:13.110 --> 00:22:16.460
and be able to figure out
something about both their

00:22:16.460 --> 00:22:18.670
frequency and their wavelength,
and know the

00:22:18.670 --> 00:22:20.570
relationship between the two.

00:22:20.570 --> 00:22:23.880
So, it's up on this screen
here now, so we'll work

00:22:23.880 --> 00:22:25.120
on the other one.

00:22:25.120 --> 00:22:28.590
If you can identify which of
these statements is correct

00:22:28.590 --> 00:22:30.940
based on what you know about
the relationship between

00:22:30.940 --> 00:22:32.880
frequency and wavelength
and also just

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:42.400
looking at the waves.

00:22:42.400 --> 00:22:42.670
Alright.

00:22:42.670 --> 00:22:49.550
So, let's give ten more
seconds on that.

00:22:49.550 --> 00:23:06.670
So, ten seconds on that.

00:23:06.670 --> 00:23:07.170
Alright.

00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:08.320
So, good job.

00:23:08.320 --> 00:23:11.920
So, most people could recognize
that light wave a

00:23:11.920 --> 00:23:13.340
has the shorter wavelength.

00:23:13.340 --> 00:23:18.240
We can see that just by looking
at the graph itself --

00:23:18.240 --> 00:23:20.950
we can see, certainly, this is
shorter from maxima to maxima.

00:23:20.950 --> 00:23:22.810
This we can't even see
the next maxima,

00:23:22.810 --> 00:23:24.010
so it's much longer.

00:23:24.010 --> 00:23:26.640
And then, we also know that
means that it has the higher

00:23:26.640 --> 00:23:29.430
frequency, because our
relationship between

00:23:29.430 --> 00:23:32.450
wavelength and frequency
are inversely related.

00:23:32.450 --> 00:23:35.190
And also, we know the
speed of light.

00:23:35.190 --> 00:23:38.410
So, if we think about if it's a
shorter wavelength, we'll be

00:23:38.410 --> 00:23:40.840
able to get a lot more
wavelengths in, in a given

00:23:40.840 --> 00:23:43.450
time, than we would for
a longer wavelength.

00:23:43.450 --> 00:23:47.400
So, we can switch back to the
notes and think about what

00:23:47.400 --> 00:23:50.230
this means, and what this means
when we're talking about

00:23:50.230 --> 00:23:52.670
all the different kinds of light
waves we have, and I've

00:23:52.670 --> 00:23:56.930
shown a bunch here, is that if
we have the wavelength, we

00:23:56.930 --> 00:23:59.670
also know the frequency
of these wavelengths.

00:23:59.670 --> 00:24:03.070
So, for example, radio waves,
which have very long

00:24:03.070 --> 00:24:07.620
wavelengths have very
low frequencies.

00:24:07.620 --> 00:24:12.620
Whereas where we go to waves
that have very short

00:24:12.620 --> 00:24:16.630
wavelengths, such a x-rays or
cosmic rays, they, in turn,

00:24:16.630 --> 00:24:19.660
have very high frequencies.

00:24:19.660 --> 00:24:22.210
So, it's important to get a
little bit of a sense of what

00:24:22.210 --> 00:24:24.510
all these different kinds
of lights do.

00:24:24.510 --> 00:24:27.610
You're absolutely not
responsible to memorize what

00:24:27.610 --> 00:24:29.950
the wavelengths of the different
types of lights are,

00:24:29.950 --> 00:24:32.870
but you do want to be
able to know the

00:24:32.870 --> 00:24:34.260
general order of them.

00:24:34.260 --> 00:24:37.700
So, if someone tells you they're
using UV light versus

00:24:37.700 --> 00:24:40.770
x-ray light, you know that the
x-ray light is, in fact, at a

00:24:40.770 --> 00:24:41.760
higher frequency.

00:24:41.760 --> 00:24:43.330
So that's the important
take-away

00:24:43.330 --> 00:24:44.810
message from this slide.

00:24:44.810 --> 00:24:47.150
If we think about these
different types of lights,

00:24:47.150 --> 00:24:50.420
microwave light, if it's
absorbed by a molecule, is a

00:24:50.420 --> 00:24:53.650
sufficient amount of frequency
and energy to get those

00:24:53.650 --> 00:24:55.370
molecules to rotate.

00:24:55.370 --> 00:24:57.200
That, of course, generates
heat, so that's how your

00:24:57.200 --> 00:24:58.300
microwaves work.

00:24:58.300 --> 00:25:02.530
If we talk about infrared light,
which is at a higher

00:25:02.530 --> 00:25:06.610
frequency here and a shorter
wavelength, infrared light

00:25:06.610 --> 00:25:08.950
when it's absorbed by molecules
actually is enough

00:25:08.950 --> 00:25:12.050
to cause molecules
now to vibrate.

00:25:12.050 --> 00:25:15.570
If we move up to the more
high-frequency and divisible

00:25:15.570 --> 00:25:19.350
light and all the way into UV
light, if you shine UV light

00:25:19.350 --> 00:25:21.830
at certain molecules, it's going
to have enough energy to

00:25:21.830 --> 00:25:25.430
actually pop those electrons
in that molecule up to a

00:25:25.430 --> 00:25:28.210
higher energy level, which will
make more sense once we

00:25:28.210 --> 00:25:31.790
talk about energy levels in
atoms, but that's what UV

00:25:31.790 --> 00:25:32.910
light can do.

00:25:32.910 --> 00:25:35.130
And actually, that's responsible
for fluorescence

00:25:35.130 --> 00:25:37.850
and phosphorescence that
you see where typically

00:25:37.850 --> 00:25:39.780
UV light comes in.

00:25:39.780 --> 00:25:42.000
So, if you use a black lamp or
something and you excite

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:44.140
something up to a higher energy
level and then it

00:25:44.140 --> 00:25:47.490
relaxes back down to its lower
energy state, it's going to

00:25:47.490 --> 00:25:50.540
emit a new wavelength of light,
which is going to be

00:25:50.540 --> 00:25:51.920
visible to you.

00:25:51.920 --> 00:25:55.610
X-rays are at even a higher
frequency, and those are

00:25:55.610 --> 00:25:59.365
sufficient to actually be
absorbed by a molecule and pop

00:25:59.365 --> 00:26:01.450
an electron all the way
out of that molecule.

00:26:01.450 --> 00:26:04.580
You can see how that would be
damaging to the integrity of

00:26:04.580 --> 00:26:08.090
that molecule, that's why x-rays
are so damaging -- you

00:26:08.090 --> 00:26:11.040
don't want to have electrons
disappearing for no good

00:26:11.040 --> 00:26:13.140
reason from your molecules that
can cause the kind of

00:26:13.140 --> 00:26:16.770
mutations we don't want to
be seeing in ourselves.

00:26:16.770 --> 00:26:18.930
And then also as we go
higher, we have gamma

00:26:18.930 --> 00:26:21.580
rays and cosmic rays.

00:26:21.580 --> 00:26:25.400
Within the visible range of what
we can see, you also want

00:26:25.400 --> 00:26:29.200
to know this relative order
that's pretty easy -- most of

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:30.850
us have memorized that
in kindergarten, so

